<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-08-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-08-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="311" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d311">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Memorandum delivered by the Chinese
                                    minister.</hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Chinese Legation</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-08-08"><hi rend="italic">August 8, 1900</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                            <p rend="center"><hi rend="italic">Cablegram from Yu Lien-Yuen, taotai
                                    of Shanghai, received by Minister Wu on the 8th of August,
                                    1900.</hi></p>
                            <p>Have received telegram from Governor Yuan Shih-Kai to the effect that
                                the Tsungli Yamen received on the 5th of August an Imperial edict
                                allowing all the foreign ministers free communication with their
                                respective governments in cipher.</p>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>